<TITLE> Nation set to celebrate Victory Day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 15 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh proudly celebrates Victory Day Sunday. On the day in 1971, the Pakistan army surrendered, ending Bangladesh's nine-month war of independence. The day's celebrations will start with a 21-gun salute at the Savar National Memorial followed by the laying of wreaths to pay tributes to the nation's war heroes who laid down their lives for independence. President Iajuddin Ahmed and chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed will be the first to lay flowers and pay respects on behalf of the nation. Social, political and educational groups are preparing to mark the occasion with daylong programmes. National flags will be hoisted atop buildings and other structures. Many civil society bodies and private citizens will also raise flags in respect. Government and semi-government buildings will be illuminated by night. Special prayers have been arranged at mosques and temples and other religious sites. A special children's programme has been arranged to be held at the Bangabandhu National Stadium, the government said in a statement. The nation began its armed struggle against the occupation of Pakistani forces on March 26, 1971 and won its victory on December 16. bdnews
